<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Reshuffle Follows Ministers' Resignations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Reshuffle Follows Ministers' Resignations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2804130194 Dakar PANA in French 1024 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2804130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Libreville, 28 Apr (AGP-GAB/PANA) -- Official 
sources in Libreville have disclosed that on 26 April, there was 
a technical reshuffle of the cabinet formed by Prime Minister 
Casimir Oye-Mba on 25 March. The reshuffle follows the 
resignation of Jean-Pierre Bagnena, leader of the opposition 
Gabonese Socialist Party, and Jean-Francois Ntoutoume Emane, 
member of parliament of the ruling Gabonese Democratic Party. 
  Mr. Bagnena refused the post of secretary of state for 
health 
because he was not consulted beforehand, while Ntoutoume Emane 
refused the post of minister of state control, decentralization, 
territorial administration, and regional integration because he 
was dissatisfied with the duties and functions assigned to his 
department. 
  The resignation of the two ministers brings the number of 
cabinet ministers down from 38 to 36. The presidential decree 
which announced the technical reshuffle also stated that the 
state secretariat for health has been scrapped. Furthermore, 
the decree stated that Pierre Nziengui Mabilat, minister of 
small- and medium- scale enterprises, has been named interim 
minister of state control, decentralization, territorial 
administration, and regional integration. 

</TEXT>

