<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Ajello `Very Happy' With Chissano Pronouncements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN's Ajello `Very Happy' With Chissano Pronouncements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2904122494 Maputo Radio Mozambique Network in Portuguese 
1030 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2904122494 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Mozambique Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Edmundo Galiza Matos] </F>
  [Text] As usual, UN Special Representative Dr. Aldo Ajello 
granted his Friday news conference in Maputo today and he 
announced that the Supervision and Control Commission [CSC] will 
meet on 3 May to try to find realistic solutions to various 
problems in the Mozambican pacification process. Aldo Ajello 
noted that the CSC meeting will try to set deadlines for closing 
down government and Mozambique National Resistance [Renamo] 
assembly areas as well as for winding up the demobilization 
process. 
  The UN special representative in Mozambique made it clear 
that he would like to see the whole process concluded in July, 
even though he agrees that could be done in June as proposed by 
the National Elections Commission, CNE, chairman. The electoral 
census is supposed to begin in June. 
  At another point in his news conference, the head of the UN 
Operations in Mozambique [Unomoz] said he was very happy with 
President of the Republic Joaquim Chissano's pronouncements in 
his provincial tours, but he called for there to be consistency 
between words and deeds. He also disclosed that the Renamo 
demobilization process is making progress and he added that a 
list has been delivered containing more than 1,000 names of men 
supposed to go back to civilian life. That process is scheduled 
to begin today and be over by 6 May, and Renamo is supposed to 
demobilize 4,000 of its soldiers. 
  Meanwhile, 4,345 government and Renamo soldiers and officers 
are undergoing training in Manica, Boane, Dondo, Nacala, and 
Catembe. The UN special representative in Mozambique also 
disclosed that $8.163 [figure as heard] million is already in 
the hands of Unomoz. That money will be used to help Renamo 
become a political party. It is expected that a further $5.173 
million will be given Renamo for that purpose, in addition to 
funds which may also be allocated by the U.S. and French 
Governments. 
  The head of Unomoz also said that $2.006 million will be 
placed with the trust fund [preceding two words in English] for 
other political parties. He explained that it will be up to 
Unomoz to manage those funds. He also disclosed that the UN 
Security Council has sent a list of five international judges to 
be part of the Electoral Court. Those judges will come from 
France, Brazil, Nicaragua, Chile, and Portugal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
