<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   CD Orders Government To Resolve Fuel Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CD Orders Government To Resolve Fuel Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2804172194 Paris AFP in French 1959 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2804172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 27 Apr (AFP) -- The human rights 
organization, Campaign for Democracy [CD], today ordered the 
Nigerian Government to put an end to the serious fuel shortage 
affecting the country by 29 April, otherwise it will call on the 
people to drive away the ruling "clique." "We want to state 
clearly and unequivocally that if the fuel crisis is not 
resolved by 29 April, by those who orchestrated it, the CD will 
call on the Nigerian people to go into the streets to drive the 
Abacha clique away," CD pointed out in a communique signed by 
its Secretary General Sylvester Odion-Akhaine, a copy of which 
was sent to AFP. 
  Furthermore, CD, a collective of some 40 student and human 
rights organizations, described the government's 26 April 
ultimatum to the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation [NNPC] 
as "hypocritical," given that "the fraud perpetrated within the 
NNPC is orchestrated by government officials," the communique 
stressed. The government has given a seven-day ultimatum to the 
NNPC to restore fuel supply in the country. Nigeria is 
currently facing one of the most serious fuel shortages in many 
years and a chaotic situation is prevailing in the country. The 
CD communique called on the country to get ready for "a great 
confrontation...because the decisive moment has come." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

