<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   PAC Demands IEC Address W. Cape Voting Irregularities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PAC Demands IEC Address W. Cape Voting Irregularities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2804143494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1419 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2804143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town April 28 SAPA -- The Pan Africanist 
Congress [PAC] would not accept the Western Cape election result 
until a range of poll-related irregularities were addressed by 
the Independent Electoral Commission [IEC], the party said on 
Thursday [28 April]. Alleging electoral sabotage by the African 
National Congress and IEC in the region, PAC Western Cape 
premier-elect Patricia de Lille said 90 per cent of local IEC 
personnel were aligned to the ANC. 
  At a news conference in the PAC's Salt River offices, she 
said PAC complaints to provincial IEC officer Mary Burton, the 
IEC Investigations Department and the National Operations Crisis 
Centre had not been handled decisively. 
  "The PAC wishes to put on record that voting in the 
Mitchell's Plain district...has been rigged. We suspect this was 
done in conspiracy with IEC officials," the PAC said in an 
official complaint to Mr Piet Colyn at the IEC's National 
Operation Centre on Tuesday. 
  Claimed irregularities between April 26 and 28 included: 

  -  IEC officials at Hanover Park telling people which party 
to vote for; 
  -  ANC party agents inside voting stations telling people which 
party to vote for; 
  -  ANC supporters intimidating voters inside the Khayelithsa 
resource centre; 
  -  The Marconi Beam polling station at Milnerton being shifted 
to 
a police station; 
  -  Party posters inside demarcated areas at three Gugulethu 
polling stations; 
  -  Ballot boxes at the Nomsa Mpongwana school, site B hall and 
Chumisa school in Khayelitsha, and the Westridge civic centre in 
Mitchell's Plain, being opened for transfer to postal bags; 
  -  Two ballot boxes and a plastic bag being removed in a private 
vehicle from the Linge lower primary school; 
  -  Three PAC party agents being refused access to the Somerset 
West town hall; 
  -  Shots fired at a PAC canvassing table by "known ANC members" 
at 
Unathi, Crossroads; 
  -  PAC branch secretary Andile Makhala being stabbed by five 
"ANC 
people" for wearing a PAC t-shirt; and 
  -  IEC officials voting twice at the Ebutsheni school, 
Khayelitsha. 


</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-1492 </DOCNO>
<HT>      "drafr083_cs94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-083-S </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Freedom Front To Protest Lack of Ballots in Alberton </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Freedom Front To Protest Lack of Ballots in Alberton </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2804115994 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in Afrikaans 
1000 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2804115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  Afrikaans </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Freedom Front has said in a statement issued in 
Pretoria the fact that ballot papers were not available in white 
areas of Alberton early this morning calls into serious question 
the freedom and fairness of the election. The front said it 
suspects that the Independent Electoral Commission [IEC] is 
being deliberately unhelpful. A complaint in this regard is to 
be handed to the IEC today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-1493 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr083_cs94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-083-S </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Viljoen Proposes Leaders Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Viljoen Proposes Leaders Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2804192694 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in Afrikaans 
1800 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2804192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  Afrikaans </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen said, as he 
put it, the chaotic state of the election has upset many people. 
General Viljoen said in Lydenburg that he was not criticizing 
the IEC [Independent Electoral Commission] because this 
commission had been entrusted with an impossible task stemming 
from wrong decisions. 
  [Begin recording] [Viljoen] I am not sure what was going on 
here, but the number of votes, the additional ballot papers that 
had to be printed has been Greek to me. I cannot understand why 
such a situation prevails, and to me this does not make sense. I 
think the situation has to be looked into very seriously. 
  [Correspondent Pieter Theron] Gen. Viljoen visited several 
polling stations in the eastern and northern Transvaal. It was 
clear that most people in these regions had already voted 
yesterday. The voting in some places took place very 
peacefully; no problems were experienced, although ballot papers 
at some voting stations were lacking. The Freedom Front 
contends that in view of numerous logistic and administrative 
problems which cropped up during the election period, a leaders' 
summit should be held immediately after the elections were 
completed. It will determine whether the election had been free 
and fair. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

