Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Violent Incidents Reported at Polling Stations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Violent Incidents Reported at Polling Stations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Gunman Fires on Bophuthatswana Voters </H4>

<F P=102> MB2804210594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2044 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2804210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mmabatho April 28 SAPA -- A white gunman who opened 
fire on voters at a polling station at Taung in Bophuthatswana 
was under police guard in hospital, SABC [South African 
Broadcasting Corporation] radio reported on Thursday [28 April] 
night. Police spokesman Col Dave George said the suspect was 
severely burnt when angry voters set his vehicle alight after 
the shooting. 
  The incident was one of several rumoured developments in the 
Western Transvaal which the Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging [AWB, 
Afrikaner Resistance Movement] has earmarked as the base for the 
Afrikaner "volkstaat" [homeland]. 
  South African Police said they could not comment on the 
incident because it occurred in an area under the control of the 
Bophuthatswana police. 
  Information filtering from the region said right-wingers 
were 
involved in the incident. 
  There were also reports that AWB members and security forces 
levelled their weapons at each other in the Rustenburg area on 
Thursday, but police could not confirm any such incident. 
  Defence force Ratel armoured vehicles and black defence 
force 
troops lined the streets of Rustenburg on Thursday when an AWB 
convoy of about 100 cars moved through the town for an AWB rally. 
  Whites in Rustenburg were seen to give the white 
right-wingers thumbs-down signs. 
  Observers said the ranks of the AWB appear to be dwindling, 
with 200 people attending Thursday's rally. Few attended a rally 
addressed by AWB leader Eugene Terreblanche in Brits last 
weekend. 
  Police on thursday continued their investigations into 
bombings on the reef. Police Commissioner Johan van der Merwe 
earlier said some of the suspects arrested were AWB members. 
  A number of right-wingers' farms had been searched for 
weapons and explosives in the past few days, according to 
Western Transvaal police sources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

