<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Survey Predicts More Manufacturing Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Survey Predicts More Manufacturing Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2603091494 Taipei CNA in English 0714 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 26 (CNA) -- Manufacturing industry 
investment is expected to increase 17.4 percent in 1994, the 
greatest increase in five years, the government reported 
Saturday [26 March]. 
  According to a report released by the Directorate General of 
Budget, Accounting and Statistics (DGBAS), key projects, those 
worth at least NT$200 million (US$7.58 million), will be the 
primary contributors to the expected boost in investment 
willingness. The report was based on a survey of 1,800 private 
enterprises. 
  Investments by large enterprises are predicted to surge by 
[figure indistinct] percent, but those by small- and 
medium-sized enterprises will fall by 7.5 percent and 14.4 
percent respectively, according to survey results. 
  "The anticipated drop in investment willingness among small 
businesses is the result of a combination of negative factors 
such as the lingering business slowdown, stringent pollution 
control requirements and a dearth of capital," a DGBAS official 
explained. 
  Nearly all sectors of the manufacturing industry indicated a 
strong desire to invest, the survey found. Machinery equipment 
investment, an index often used to gauge investment willingness, 
was predicted to increase to a record high of 20.3 percent over 
1993 levels. 
  The metal industry is projected to lead the investment 
spree, 
surging 64.3 percent over 1993. Just as dynamic will be 
electrical accessories and appliances, which are predicted to 
jump 53.9 percent. 
  The report also forecast a 9.3 percent growth in revenues 
for 
the manufacturing industry as compared with the 6.9 percent 
growth rate registered in 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

