<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Suffers `Serious Drought' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Suffers `Serious Drought' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2703050394 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0255 GMT 
26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2703050394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 26 (CNS) -- Early spring drought in 
Beijing is seriously threatening agriculture and dwellers living 
in mountainous areas there. The municipal government has called 
for the entire city to take urgent measures to combat the 
drought. 
  According to the municipal meteorological bureau, Beijing 
has 
had no soaking rain for fifteen months with an average rainfall 
of only 2.1 millimetres between last December until now, less 
than one- quarter of average rainfall in the same period in past 
years, making this fourth most serious drought year for the city 
this century. 
  The two biggest reservoirs in Beijing, the Guangting and 
Miyun reservoirs have seen their water storage falling by 600 
million cubic metres from that of the same period last year. 
Water storage in another 12 medium-scale reservoirs has also 
fallen by 45 million cubic metres. The city's underground water 
level has also dropped to a large extent. 
  The drought is seriously threatening agriculture and the 
people's lives there with 2.42 million mu wheat and over 800,000 
mu land area under spring sowing in urgent need of irrigation. 
The city's mountainous areas are now suffering insufficient 
water supply. 
  The municipal government has called for the whole city to 
combat the drought. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

