<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tianjin Reports `Sustained' Growth in Exports in 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tianjin Reports `Sustained' Growth in Exports in 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2603013494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0114 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603013494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, March 26 (XINHUA) -- North China's port 
city of Tianjin is experiencing sustained growth in exports with 
a gross export value reaching 360 million U.S. dollars in the 
first two months of this year, a sizzling 20.4 percent rise from 
the same period in 1993. 
  And according to local economists, the surge will continue 
in 
the coming months. Total exports this year are expected to 
reach 2.3 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of more than 20 
percent over last year. 
  Figures from the municipal foreign trade and export 
department show that the city's export growth has paralleled its 
economic gains over the past three years. 
  The city has achieved a record export growth rate of 10 
percent in the past three years from 1991. The gross export 
volume in 1993 topped 1.94 billion U.S. dollars, more than 
doubling the amount in 1978. 
  Of the goods exported, about 82 percent were industrial end- 
products and 18 percent primary products; the products exported 
by foreign-funded firms and private businesses also rose sharply. 
  And many of these products have already entered the world 
market, spreading over 153 countries and regions throughout the 
world. 
  About 55 percent of the city's exports last year went to 
Hong 
Kong, Japan and the United States, and exports to East European 
countries and Russia have also been expanded over the past few 
years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

