<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhejiang's Ningbo Becomes Key Transit Port for Iron Ore </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhejiang's Ningbo Becomes Key Transit Port for Iron Ore </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3103102994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0831 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3103102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ningbo, March 31 (XINHUA) -- The Beilun Port of 
this coastal city in Zhejiang Province, one of China's four 
major deepwater harbors, has become a key transit port for 
imported iron ore. 
  So far, 14 large and medium-sized iron and steel complexes 
along the Chang Jiang river and interior parts of the country 
have imported iron ore via the port. 
  The special wharf of the port began to serve the Shanghai 
Baoshan Iron and Steel Complex, a large modern enterprise, in 
1982 and later the Wuhan Iron and Steel Complex. 
  To meet the needs of different iron and steel plants, the 
Beilun Port has expanded its stockyards three times to raise its 
storage capacity from the original 500,000 tons to one million 
tons at present. 
  A survey shows that the port has handled 40 million tons of 
imported iron ore in 20 varieties so far. 
  At present, construction of another iron ore wharf able to 
accommodate 300,000-dwt [deadweight ton] ships is proceeding 
well. 
  It will be able to handle between 28 million tons and 30 
million tons of iron ore a year upon completion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-1524 </DOCNO>
